Concatenate dataframes

In [2]:
# Import the NYSE and NASDAQ listings
nyse = pd.read_excel('listings.xlsx', sheetname='nyse', na_values='n/a')
nasdaq = pd.read_excel('listings.xlsx', sheetname='nasdaq', na_values='n/a')

# Add Exchange reference columns
nyse['Exchange'] = 'NYSE'
nasdaq['Exchange'] = 'NASDAQ'

# Concatenate DataFrames  
combined_listings = pd.concat([nyse, nasdaq]) 
print(combined_listings.info())

# Concatenate all dataframes in different worksheets of excel

xls = pd.ExcelFile('listings.xlsx')
exchanges = xls.sheet_names

# Create an empty list: listings
listings=[]

# Import the data
for exchange in exchanges:
    listing = pd.read_excel(xls, sheetname=exchange, na_values='n/a')
    listing['Exchange'] = exchange
    listings.append(listing)

# Concatenate the listings: listing_data
listing_data = pd.concat(listings)

# Inspect the results
print(listing_data.info())

import matplotlib.pyplot as plt
import matplotlib
plt.style.use('seaborn-darkgrid')
# Import DataReader
from pandas_datareader.data import DataReader

# Import date
from datetime import date

# Set start and end dates
start = date(2016,1,1)
end = date(2016,12,31)

# Set the ticker
ticker = 'AAPL'

# Set the data source
data_source = 'google'  ## data from google finance

# Import the stock prices
stock_prices = DataReader(ticker, data_source, start, end)

# Display and inspect the result
print(stock_prices.head())
stock_prices.info()

# Plot Close
stock_prices['Close'].plot(title=ticker,figsize=(8,5))
matplotlib.rc('xtick', labelsize=12) 
matplotlib.rc('ytick', labelsize=12) 
plt.show()

Largest consumer services company¶

In [9]:
# Get the ticker of the largest (in Market Capitalization) company across all three exchange markets (using idxmax())

from pandas_datareader.data import DataReader
from datetime import date

xls = pd.ExcelFile('listings.xlsx')
exchanges = xls.sheet_names
listings=[]
for exchange in exchanges:
    listing = pd.read_excel(xls, sheetname=exchange, na_values='n/a')
    listing['Exchange'] = exchange
    listings.append(listing)
listings = pd.concat(listings)

# Set the index of listings to Stock Symbol
listings = listings.set_index('Stock Symbol')

# Get ticker of the largest Consumer Services company
ticker = listings.loc[listings.Sector=='Consumer Services', 'Market Capitalization'].idxmax()

start = date(2012,1,1)
data = DataReader(ticker,'google',start)
data[['Close', 'Volume']].plot(secondary_y='Volume', title=ticker,alpha=0.8,figsize=(15,6))
plt.show()

Largest consumer services company listed after 1997¶

In [10]:
xls = pd.ExcelFile('listings.xlsx')
exchanges = xls.sheet_names
listings=[]
for exchange in exchanges:
    listing = pd.read_excel(xls, sheetname=exchange, na_values='n/a')
    listing['Exchange'] = exchange
    listings.append(listing)
listings = pd.concat(listings)

# Set Stock Symbol as the index
listings = listings.set_index('Stock Symbol')

# Get ticker of the largest consumer services company listed after 1997
ticker = listings.loc[(listings.Sector == 'Consumer Services') & (listings['IPO Year'] > 1998), 'Market Capitalization'].idxmax()
name_company=listings.loc[ticker,'Company Name']

# Set the start date
start = date(1998,1,1)

# Import the stock data
data = DataReader(ticker,'google',start)

# Plot Close and Volume
data[['Close', 'Volume']].plot(secondary_y='Volume',title=name_company,alpha=0.8,figsize=(15,6))
plt.show()

Stock prices for the 3 largest financial companies¶

In [11]:
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt
from pandas_datareader.data import DataReader

# Import date
from datetime import date

xls = pd.ExcelFile('listings.xlsx')
exchanges = xls.sheet_names
listings=[]
for exchange in exchanges:
    listing = pd.read_excel(xls, sheetname=exchange, na_values='n/a')
    listing['Exchange'] = exchange
    listings.append(listing)
listings = pd.concat(listings)

listings.set_index('Stock Symbol',inplace=True)

# Get ticker of 3 largest finance companies
top_3_companies = listings.loc[listings.Sector == 'Finance','Market Capitalization'].nlargest(n=3)
# Convert index to list
top_3_tickers = top_3_companies.index.tolist()

start = date(2012,1,1)
data = DataReader(top_3_tickers,'google',start)  # we obtain a panel (3 dimensions dataframe)
# Convert panel to dataframe
data2 = data.to_frame()  # we obtain a dataframe with multiIndex

# Unstack and inspect result
data3 = data2['Close'].unstack()
data3.columns = listings.loc[top_3_tickers,'Company Name']
print(data3.info())

data3.plot(subplots=True,figsize=(13,11))
plt.show()

Companies by sector on all exchanges¶

In [12]:
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt

xls = pd.ExcelFile('listings.xlsx')
# Extract sheet names
exchanges = xls.sheet_names
# Create listings dictionary with all sheet data
listings = pd.read_excel(xls, sheetname=exchanges, na_values='n/a')

# Iterate over exchanges then plot
for exchange in exchanges:
    sectors = listings[exchange].Sector.value_counts()
    # Sort in descending order and plot
    sectors.sort_values(ascending=False).plot(kind='bar',figsize=(8,5))
    plt.title(exchange+' companies, by sector')
    plt.show()

Technology IPOs by year on all exchanges¶

In [13]:
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt

# Import date
from datetime import date

xls = pd.ExcelFile('listings.xlsx')
exchanges = xls.sheet_names
listings=[]
for exchange in exchanges:
    listing = pd.read_excel(xls, sheetname=exchange, na_values='n/a')
    listing['Exchange'] = exchange
    listings.append(listing)
listing_data = pd.concat(listings)

# Select tech companies
tech_companies = listing_data[listing_data.Sector == 'Technology']

# Create ipo_years
ipo_years = tech_companies['IPO Year']

# Drop missing values and convert to int
ipo_years = ipo_years.dropna().astype(int)

# Count values, sort by year, and create a bar plot
ipo_years.value_counts().sort_index().plot(kind='bar', title='Tech IPOs by Year',figsize=(15,5))

plt.xticks(rotation=45)
plt.show()

Different Statistics of Income per Capita¶

In [14]:
import pandas as pd
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt
import numpy as np

income = pd.read_csv('per_capita_income.csv')

# Inspect the result
income.info()

# Sort the data by income
income = income.sort_values('Income per Capita', ascending=False)

# Mean, median and mode
print(income['Income per Capita'].mean())
print(income['Income per Capita'].median())

income['Income per Capita round'] = round(income['Income per Capita'],-3)
print(income.head())
print(income['Income per Capita round'].mode())

# variance and standard deviation
print("{0:.4e}".format(income['Income per Capita'].var()))
print("{0:.4e}".format(income['Income per Capita'].std()))

# quantiles
quantiles = income['Income per Capita'].quantile([0.25,0.75])
print(quantiles)

# interquartile range
iqr = quantiles[.75] - quantiles[.25]
print(iqr)

# deciles
quantiles = np.arange(0.1,.91,0.1)
deciles = income['Income per Capita'].quantile(quantiles)
print(deciles)

# Plot deciles as a bar chart
deciles.plot(kind='bar', title='Global Income per Capita - Deciles',figsize=(7,5))
matplotlib.rc('xtick', labelsize=12) 
matplotlib.rc('ytick', labelsize=12) 
plt.tight_layout()
plt.show()

# Plot distribution (barplot and kernel density estimation (KDE))
import seaborn as sns
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt
sns.distplot(income['Income per Capita'])
plt.title('Global Income per Capita - Bar plot and KDE')
plt.show()

# Plot barplot and rugplot
sns.distplot(income['Income per Capita'], bins=50, kde=False, rug=True)
plt.title('Global Income per Capita - Bar plot and rug plot')
plt.show()

# Distribution
inc_per_capita = income['Income per Capita']
# Filter out incomes above the 95th percentile
inc_per_capita = inc_per_capita[inc_per_capita < inc_per_capita.quantile(0.95)]
ax = sns.distplot(inc_per_capita,bins=20)
ax.axvline(inc_per_capita.mean(), color='b',label='mean')
ax.axvline(inc_per_capita.median(), color='g',label='median')
plt.legend()
plt.show()

plt.show()

# Iterate over the three columns
plt.subplots(figsize=(8,5))
for column in growth.columns:
    sns.distplot(growth[column], hist=False, label=column)

import pandas as pd
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt

nyse = pd.read_excel('listings.xlsx', sheetname='nyse', na_values='n/a')
nyse.info()

# Create market_cap_m
nyse['market_cap_m'] = nyse['Market Capitalization'].div(1e6)

# Drop market cap column
nyse = nyse.drop('Market Capitalization', axis=1)

# Group nyse by sector
mcap_by_sector = nyse.groupby('Sector')

# Calculate median
median_mcap_by_sector = mcap_by_sector.market_cap_m.median()

# Plot and show as horizontal bar chart
plt.subplots(figsize=(10,7))
median_mcap_by_sector.plot(kind='barh', title='NYSE - Median Market Capitalization')
plt.xlabel('(in million USD)')

plt.show()

Median market capitalization by IPO year¶

In [18]:
import pandas as pd
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt

nyse = pd.read_excel('listings.xlsx', sheetname='nyse', na_values='n/a')

# Create market_cap_m
nyse['market_cap_m'] = nyse['Market Capitalization'].div(1e6)

# Select companies with IPO after 1985
nyse = nyse[nyse['IPO Year'] > 1985]

# Drop missing values and convert to integers
nyse['IPO Year'] = nyse['IPO Year'].dropna().astype(int)

# Calculate the median market cap by IPO Year and sort the index
ipo_by_year = nyse.groupby('IPO Year').market_cap_m.median().sort_index()

# Plot results as a bar chart
ipo_by_year.plot(kind='barh',figsize=(10,10))
matplotlib.rc('xtick', labelsize=12) 
matplotlib.rc('ytick', labelsize=12) 
plt.show()

Median market capitalization by exchange and sector¶

In [20]:
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt
import pandas as pd

xls = pd.ExcelFile('listings.xlsx')
exchanges = xls.sheet_names
listings=[]
for exchange in exchanges:
    listing = pd.read_excel(xls, sheetname=exchange, na_values='n/a')
    listing['Exchange'] = exchange
    listings.append(listing)
listings = pd.concat(listings)

listings['market_cap_m'] = listings['Market Capitalization'].div(1e6)
listings.drop('Market Capitalization', axis=1, inplace=True)

# Group listings by Sector and Exchange
by_sector_exchange = listings.groupby(['Sector', 'Exchange'])

# Calculate the median market cap
mcap_by_sector_exchange = by_sector_exchange.market_cap_m.median()

# Display the head of the result
print(mcap_by_sector_exchange.head())

# Unstack mcap_by_sector_exchange
mcap_unstacked = mcap_by_sector_exchange.unstack()

# Plot as a bar chart
mcap_unstacked.plot(kind='bar', title='Median Market Capitalization by Exchange',figsize=(10,6))
plt.xlabel('(in million USD)')
plt.xticks(rotation=80)
matplotlib.rc('xtick', labelsize=12) 
matplotlib.rc('ytick', labelsize=12) 
plt.show()

IPO timeline for all exchanges - countplot¶

In [22]:
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt
import pandas as pd
import seaborn as sns

xls = pd.ExcelFile('listings.xlsx')
exchanges = xls.sheet_names
listings=[]
for exchange in exchanges:
    listing = pd.read_excel(xls, sheetname=exchange, na_values='n/a')
    listing['Exchange'] = exchange
    listings.append(listing)
listings = pd.concat(listings)

# Select IPOs after 2000
listings = listings[listings['IPO Year'] > 2000]

# Convert IPO Year to integer
listings['IPO Year'] = listings['IPO Year'].astype(int)

# Create a countplot
plt.subplots(figsize=(11,6))
sns.countplot(x='IPO Year', hue='Exchange', data=listings)
plt.xticks(rotation=45)
plt.legend(loc=2) # legend at upper left location
matplotlib.rc('xtick', labelsize=12) 
matplotlib.rc('ytick', labelsize=12) 
plt.show()

Market capitalization by IPO Year and Exchange - seaborn barplot¶

In [23]:
# The seaborn barplot() function shows point estimates and confidence intervals of a parameter as rectangular bars
# the default parameter displays the mean, but we can pass a particular numpy function to its estimator parameter.

import pandas as pd
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt
import numpy as np
import seaborn as sns

xls = pd.ExcelFile('listings.xlsx')
exchanges = xls.sheet_names
listings=[]
for exchange in exchanges:
    listing = pd.read_excel(xls, sheetname=exchange, na_values='n/a')
    listing['Exchange'] = exchange
    listings.append(listing)
listings = pd.concat(listings)

listings = listings[listings['IPO Year'] > 2000]
listings['IPO Year'] = listings['IPO Year'].astype(int)

listings['market_cap_m'] = listings['Market Capitalization'].div(1e6)
listings.drop('Market Capitalization', axis=1, inplace=True)

# Create barplot
plt.subplots(figsize=(11,6))
sns.barplot(x='IPO Year', y='market_cap_m', data=listings)
plt.xticks(rotation=45)
plt.show()

# Create second barplot
plt.subplots(figsize=(11,6))
sns.barplot(x='Exchange', y='market_cap_m', data=listings, estimator=np.median)
plt.xticks(rotation=45)
matplotlib.rc('xtick', labelsize=12) 
matplotlib.rc('ytick', labelsize=12) 
plt.show()

Market capitalization by Sector and Exchange - seaborn pointplot¶

In [24]:
import pandas as pd
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt
import matplotlib
import numpy as np
import seaborn as sns

xls = pd.ExcelFile('listings.xlsx')
exchanges = xls.sheet_names
listings=[]
for exchange in exchanges:
    listing = pd.read_excel(xls, sheetname=exchange, na_values='n/a')
    listing['Exchange'] = exchange
    listings.append(listing)
listings = pd.concat(listings)

listings['market_cap_m'] = listings['Market Capitalization'].div(1e6)

# Exclude outliers
listings = listings[listings.market_cap_m < listings.market_cap_m.quantile(.95)]

# Create the pointplot
plt.subplots(figsize=(13,7))
sns.pointplot(x='Sector', y='market_cap_m', hue='Exchange', data=listings,size=8)
plt.xticks(rotation=80)
matplotlib.rc('xtick', labelsize=12) 
matplotlib.rc('ytick', labelsize=12) 
plt.show()
